english:
  title: Record of the Hall of Solitary Joy
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Someone once said to me: "In the Song dynasty, Sima Guanshi and Fan Xiweng both rose to the position of Chancellor through their mastery of Confucian learning. Their virtue and accomplishments were equally matched. Fan Gong taught: 'Worry for the world before others do, rejoice in the world after others do.' His aspirations were grand and his benevolence vast—surely he could guide the ruler aright and bestow blessings upon the people, thus saving all under heaven. The Way of the sages does not prize mere self-cultivation but seeks to extend goodness to others. Therefore, Confucius found joy when friends came from afar, while Mencius found joy among the multitudes. Both these men were followers of Confucius and Mencius. Fan Gong's aspirations were indeed vast, yet Sima Gong named his garden 'Hall of Solitary Joy.' Why would he do so?"

    I replied: "The joy of the gentleman has both root and branch. What is attained within the breast is the root; what manifests in affecting things is the branch. When we extend the joy within our breast to reach all things, then heaven, earth, and the ten thousand things become as one body with us, and nothing lies outside our joy. Yet among beings, our kind deserves priority in extending this joy. Thus comes the saying: 'How joyful when friends visit from distant places,' and 'How joyful to nurture talented minds.' Such joy finds expression in the poems of an age and transmits its blessings far into future generations.

    When this joy reaches outward to all things—from the great harmony of birds, beasts, and fish to the humble grasses left uncut in the courtyard—both things and self are embraced within one great accord, each finding its place. What greater joy could there be? Yet extending oneself to all things is difficult to perfect. When our own joy remains unfulfilled, we ourselves become troubled. Even Yao and Shun lamented their inability to provide universal care—how much more so for those of lesser stature?

    But the joy attained within the breast remains unchanged by circumstance, ever present and self-sustaining. Finding no fault within oneself and shame before heaven and earth—this is Solitary Joy. Fan Gong spoke from the ultimate extension of joy to all things; Sima Gong illuminated its realization through self-attainment. Without such joy rooted within, one cannot truly extend oneself fully to all things. The words of these two men illuminate each other.

    Yet even among those who attain joy within themselves, there are degrees of depth and shallowness. The noble disciples of Confucius received direct teaching from the sage, yet their attainments differed. Zilu's determination remained unmoved even when his robes were tattered—a great spirit indeed. Yet when compared to Zengdian, who spoke of singing among youths and elders while returning home, with such unhurried ease in his breast, there is a difference. These distinctions appear in how their joy extended to things. But Yan Hui, who said he would not change his joy though living on meager rations in a humble alley, closely approaches Confucius who said, 'Eating coarse rice, drinking water, and pillowinig on my arm—joy dwells even there.' This is one who truly attains joy full within the breast—true Solitary Joy.

    A thousand years hence, Master Zhu Xi understood this deeply. He would ask his students to seek out what it was that Confucius and Yan Hui found joyful. The two Cheng brothers too attained insight here. Master Zhu's breast was clear as pure wind after rain, like sunlight breaking through clouds—only through such clarity could one reach the state of joy that Confucius and Yan Hui knew. Is this not the root?"

    The man nodded and withdrew. Some time later, I visited Vu Sang-gong of Danyang. He had retired from his position as Chancellor and lived in leisure. He had inscribed his hall with the words "Solitary Joy" and asked me to write an account, saying: "Though I admire Sima Guanshi, my meaning is not entirely derived from his. When I behold spring flowers in the morning, flowers are pleasant to enjoy—yet the flowers do not share my joy. When I observe autumn moons on a clear night, the moon is pleasant to contemplate—yet the moon does not share my joy. The strange wonders of cloud-crowned peaks, the pristine beauty of pine-laden snow—all are delightful to observe. Rare bird songs and the sound of gentle rain are pleasant to hear. Though countless things touch my eyes and ears and gladden my heart, not a single thing truly shares in what my heart finds joyful. Is this not what we call Solitary Joy?

    "I read books alone, needing no discourse with others. I recite poems alone, seeking no exchange with companions. I drink wine alone, requiring no guests present. I rise late, sleep when tired, sometimes wander the garden, sometimes recline on my bed—going wherever my heart inclines, companioned only by my shadow. This is my Solitary Joy in this life of leisure.

    "When I ponder past and present, the endless transformations of rise and fall, gain and loss appear before me. What has gone is but dream, not truth. How can I be certain what is yet to come will prove real? Unworthy though I am, I have served long in high office and escaped censure; I have endured misfortune yet emerged unscathed. I have lived to see a sage-ruler's reign and know a peaceful age in my declining years—what greater fortune could there be? I lament the ancients who have passed away and cherish that my own breath still remains. While all the world bustles in endless pursuit, I alone desire nothing and am thereby complete. This is my Solitary Joy as I reflect upon myself.

    "Write this account for me," he said.

    I could not decline. I presented what I had once discussed with another and continued: "When people harbor desires, their hearts become agitated and worries multiply. Without desires, heavenly principles manifest naturally, and at each moment one finds peace and joy. Your Excellency has long studied the learning of Zhou and Cheng while investigating the joy that Confucius and Yan Hui knew. In your time of prominence, you carried Fan Xiweng's aspirations for the world's welfare and practiced Sima Guanshi's virtue in your governance. When you withdrew from office, you endured the cruelest hardships, yet your spirit remained unmoved. Sorrow and joy, honor and disgrace—all that comes from without—pass before you like the alternation of seasons, yet you neither rejoice nor grieve among them. You trust only yourself, content in yourself, preserving the joy that dwells within your breast. This is what the multitude cannot know, what only the gentleman truly attains.

    "Moreover, having accomplished your work and earned your name, you withdrew and now spend your remaining years in leisure and ease. This differs not from Sima Gong's serene life in Luoyang. Surely naming your hall 'Solitary Joy' is fitting. Ah, your heart's joy fills your breast and manifests throughout this hall. Should this joy extend outward from here, even the vastness of heaven and earth, the multitude of all things, might be harmonized into one within this hall."
  footnotes:
    - Fan Xiweng (范希文, 989-1052) was a Northern Song statesman and philosopher known for his dedication to public service and moral governance.
    - Sima Guanshi (司馬君實, 1019-1086) was a Song-dynasty statesman and historian who retired to Luoyang and lived in solitude there.
    - The "joy that Confucius and Yan Hui knew" refers to the spiritual contentment achieved through virtue and self-cultivation, independent of external circumstances.
    - Yan Hui (顏回) was Confucius's most beloved and most virtuous disciple, known for his unwavering commitment to the Way despite poverty.
    - Zengdian (曾點) was the father of Zengzi; he is famous for his response in the Analects about what he would most desire, expressing a natural joy in simple living.
    - The "light wind and clear moon" (光風霽月) is a common Chinese metaphor for a clear, unclouded mind and serene spirit.
